{"TopicId":189011,"ForumId":104,"TopicTitle":"Kopernicus Space Center Help","CreatedByName":"Linktopia","CreatedById":200843,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-18T10:19:46Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"Linktopia","CreatedById":200843,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-18T10:19:46Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI got the \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Kerbal Space Center\u0022\u003EKSC\u003C/abbr\u003E on the\u00A0correct planet, however when the game loads into the space center view its black or it shows whatever is behind the planet\u003Cimg alt=\u0022dHNS3RL.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002256.47\u0022 height=\u0022578\u0022 width=\u00221024\u0022 src=\u0022https://i.imgur.com/dHNS3RL.png\u0022\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022fiLX4po.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002256.47\u0022 height=\u0022578\u0022 width=\u00221024\u0022 src=\u0022https://i.imgur.com/fiLX4po.png\u0022\u003E\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222019-10-18T11:46:48Z\u0022 title=\u002210/18/2019 11:46  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00224 yr\u0022\u003EOctober 18, 2019\u003C/time\u003E by Linktopia\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003Cbr\u003EJokes with a pal\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Galileo","CreatedById":150430,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-18T12:17:12Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIf you are reparenting Kerbin, or moving the \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Kerbal Space Center\u0022\u003EKSC\u003C/abbr\u003E to a different body that orbits anything other than The Sun, you get bugs, much like the one you are seeing. There is nothing you can do to fix it except moving the body\u0027s orbit back around the sun.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt\u0027s a well known bug, and that\u0027s why you don\u0027t see very many planet packs that do that.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222019-10-18T12:18:06Z\u0022 title=\u002210/18/2019 12:18  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00224 yr\u0022\u003EOctober 18, 2019\u003C/time\u003E by Galileo\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"}]}